                  <additions>
                  <list>
                    <item xml:id="e1">
                    <desc>
                    Part of the collection of Haroutune Nazarian, who had microfilms made of his Ethiopian manuscripts and the microfilms sent to the Institute of Ethiopian Studies. They were digitized by EMIP workers in Addis Ababa in the first half of 2010
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a1">
                    <locus target="#Inside Cover" facs="001">Fols. Inside, </locus>
                    <desc>
                    a piece of paper is attached inside the front cover.  It reads: The contents (sic) is: I. Psalms. II Song of Salamonis; III. Prophets Songs. IV. Weddasse Miryam. service-prayer etc
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e2">
                    <locus target="#1r" facs="001">Fol. 1r</locus>
                    <desc>
                    a name plate indicates this book is “Ex Libris Haroutune Hazarian” and is 289
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <locus target="#48r" facs="048">Fol. 48r</locus>
                    <desc>
                    The midpoint of the Psalms is not marked
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <locus target="#90r #90v" facs="090 091">Fols. 90r, 90v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2000Mazmur#Ps151">Psalms of
                                                  David, Psalmus 151</title> has three of the four plusses that make up the long version.  It lacks the second plus, “abominable.”
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e5">
                    <locus target="#93v" facs="094">Fol. 93v</locus>
                    <desc>
                    The Fourth Biblical Canticle is "Prayer of Hana, prophetess, mother of Samuel."
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e6">
                    <desc>
                      <title type="complete" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT2509Weddas">Wǝddāse
                                                  Māryām</title> are laid out to begin on Monday and culminate on Sunday
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a2">
                    <locus target="#105r" facs="105">Fol. 105r</locus>
                    <desc type="OwnershipNote">
                    Record: Note of ownership and sale: The owner of the book is <foreign xml:lang="gez">ሀብተ ወልድ</foreign>, who bought it with his own money. Witnesses and judge are listed along with buyer and seller
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a3">
                    <locus target="#116v" facs="117">Fol. 116v</locus>
                    <desc type="RecordTransaction">
                    Record of purchase (of book?) for <foreign xml:lang="gez">በኩል ወርቅ</foreign>, “half a gold.” Witnesses are listed
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e7">
                    <locus target="#121r" facs="121">Fol. 121r</locus>
                    <desc>
                    The microfilm information plate (image 121) indicates that the manuscript was microfilmed in 1982 and assigned the number 98
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                  </list>
                </additions>
